# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: code-generation-embedded
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] In computer science, **automatic programming** is a type of computer programming in which some mechanism generates a computer program, to allow human programmers to write the code at a higher abstraction level.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] There has been little agreement on the precise definition of automatic programming, mostly because its meaning has changed over time.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] David Parnas, tracing the history of "automatic programming" in published research, noted that in the 1940s it described automation of the manual process of punching paper tape.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Later it referred to translation of high-level programming languages like Fortran and ALGOL.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] One of the earliest programs identifiable as a compiler is named Autocode.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Program synthesis is one type of automatic programming where a procedure is created from scratch, based on mathematical requirements.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Mildred Koss, an early UNIVAC programmer, explains: "Writing machine code involved several tedious steps—breaking down a process into discrete instructions, assigning specific memory locations to all the commands, and managing the I/O buffers.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] After following these steps to implement mathematical routines, a sub-routine library, and sorting programs, our task was to look at the larger programming process.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] We needed to understand how we might reuse tested code and have the machine help in programming.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] As we programmed, we examined the process and tried to think of ways to abstract these steps to incorporate them into higher-level language.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] The goal is to improve programmer productivity.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] It is often related to code-reuse topics such as component-based software engineering.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Modern programming languages are well supported by tools like Json4Swift (Swift) and Json2Kotlin (Kotlin).
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] These application generators supported COBOL inserts and overrides.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] A macro processor, such as the C preprocessor, which replaces patterns in source code according to relatively simple rules, is a simple form of source-code generator.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Source-to-source code generation tools also exist.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Large language models such as ChatGPT are capable of generating a program's source code from a description of the program given in a natural language.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Many relational database management systems (RDBMS) provide a function that will export the content of the database as SQL data definition queries, which may then be executed to re-import the tables and their data, or migrate them to another RDBMS.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Some languages use *annotations* to generate source code and inject it.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] For example, this is done in Java and Kotlin using annotations, for example the Project Lombok library which runs at compile time with an annotation processor.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] There has been a C++ proposal to add token sequence injection using compile-time reflective programming (reflection).
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] A low-code development platform (LCDP) is software that provides an environment programmers use to create application software through graphical user interfaces and configuration instead of traditional computer programming.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Vibe coding is a software development practice assisted by artificial intelligence (AI) where the software developer describes a project or task in a prompt to a large language model (LLM) which generates source code automatically.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Vibe coding may involve accepting AI-generated code without thorough review of the output, instead relying on results and follow-up prompts to guide changes.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] The term was coined in February 2025 by computer scientist Andrej Karpathy, a co-founder of OpenAI and former AI leader at Tesla.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Merriam-Webster listed the term in March 2025 as a "slang & trending" expression.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] It was named the *Collins English Dictionary* Word of the Year for 2025.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Advocates of vibe coding say that it allows even amateur programmers to produce software without the extensive training and skills required for software engineering.
[src:code-generation-embedded/automatic-programming] Critics point out a lack of accountability, maintainability, and an increased risk of introducing security vulnerabilities in the resulting software.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] In computer programming, **dataflow programming** is a programming paradigm that models a program as a directed graph of the data flowing between operations, thus implementing dataflow principles and architecture.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming languages share some features of functional languages, and were generally developed in order to bring some functional concepts to a language more suitable for numeric processing.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Some authors use the term *datastream* instead of *dataflow* to avoid confusion with dataflow computing or dataflow architecture, based on an indeterministic machine paradigm.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programming was pioneered by Jack Dennis and his graduate students at MIT in the 1960s.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Traditionally, a program is modelled as a series of operations happening in a specific order; this may be referred to as sequential, procedural, control flow (indicating that the program chooses a specific path), or imperative programming.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] The program focuses on commands, in line with the von Neumann vision of sequential programming, where data is normally "at rest".
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] In contrast, dataflow programming emphasizes the movement of data and models programs as a series of connections.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Explicitly defined inputs and outputs connect operations, which function like black boxes.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] An operation runs as soon as all of its inputs become valid.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Thus, dataflow languages are inherently parallel and can work well in large, decentralized systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] One of the key concepts in computer programming is the idea of state, essentially a snapshot of various conditions in the system.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Most programming languages require a considerable amount of state information, which is generally hidden from the programmer.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Often, the computer itself has no idea which piece of information encodes the enduring state.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] This is a serious problem, as the state information needs to be shared across multiple processors in parallel processing machines.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Most languages force the programmer to add extra code to indicate which data and parts of the code are important to the state.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] This code tends to be both expensive in terms of performance, as well as difficult to read or debug.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Explicit parallelism is one of the main reasons for the poor performance of Enterprise Java Beans when building data-intensive, non-OLTP applications.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Where a sequential program can be imagined as a single worker moving between tasks (operations), a dataflow program is more like a series of workers on an assembly line, each doing a specific task whenever materials are available.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Since the operations are only concerned with the availability of data inputs, they have no hidden state to track, and are all "ready" at the same time.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs are represented in different ways.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] A traditional program is usually represented as a series of text instructions, which is reasonable for describing a serial system which pipes data between small, single-purpose tools that receive, process, and return.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Dataflow programs start with an input, perhaps the command line parameters, and illustrate how that data is used and modified.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] The flow of data is explicit, often visually illustrated as a line or pipe.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] In terms of encoding, a dataflow program might be implemented as a hash table, with uniquely identified inputs as the keys, used to look up pointers to the instructions.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] When any operation completes, the program scans down the list of operations until it finds the first operation where all inputs are currently valid, and runs it.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] When that operation finishes, it will typically output data, thereby making another operation become valid.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] For parallel operation, only the list needs to be shared; it is the state of the entire program.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Thus the task of maintaining state is removed from the programmer and given to the language's runtime.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] On machines with a single processor core where an implementation designed for parallel operation would simply introduce overhead, this overhead can be removed completely by using a different runtime.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Some recent dataflow libraries such as Differential/Timely Dataflow have used incremental computing for much more efficient data processing.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] A pioneer dataflow language was BLOck DIagram (BLODI), published in 1961 by John Larry Kelly, Jr., Carol Lochbaum and Victor A.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Vyssotsky for specifying sampled data systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] A BLODI specification of functional units (amplifiers, adders, delay lines, etc.) and their interconnections was compiled into a single loop that updated the entire system for one clock tick.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] In a 1966 Ph.D. thesis, *The On-line Graphical Specification of Computer Procedures*, Bert Sutherland created one of the first graphical dataflow programming frameworks in order to make parallel programming easier.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Subsequent dataflow languages were often developed at the large supercomputer labs.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] SISAL, a popular dataflow language developed at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, looks like most statement-driven languages, but variables should be assigned once.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] This allows the compiler to easily identify the inputs and outputs.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] A number of offshoots of SISAL have been developed, including SAC, *Single Assignment C*, which tries to remain as close to the popular C programming language as possible.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] The United States Navy funded development of signal processing graph notation (SPGN) and ACOS starting in the early 1980s.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] This is in use on a number of platforms in the field today.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] A more radical concept is Prograph, in which programs are constructed as graphs onscreen, and variables are replaced entirely with lines linking inputs to outputs.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] Prograph was originally written on the Macintosh, which remained single-processor until the introduction of the DayStar Genesis MP in 1996.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] There are many hardware architectures oriented toward the efficient implementation of dataflow programming models.
[src:code-generation-embedded/dataflow-programming] MIT's tagged token dataflow architecture was designed by Greg Papadopoulos.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] An **embedded system** is a specialized computer system—a combination of a computer processor, computer memory, and input/output peripheral devices—that has a dedicated function within a larger mechanical or electronic system.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] It is embedded as part of a complete device, often including electrical or electronic hardware and mechanical parts.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Embedded systems control many devices in common use.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In 2009, it was estimated that 98% of all microprocessors manufactured were used in embedded systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Because an embedded system typically controls physical operations of the machine that it is embedded within, it often has real-time computing constraints.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Modern embedded systems are often based on microcontrollers (i.e., microprocessors with integrated memory and peripheral interfaces), but ordinary microprocessors (using external chips for memory and peripheral interface circuits) are also common, especially in more complex systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In either case, the processor(s) used may be types ranging from general purpose to those specialized in a certain class of computations, or even custom designed for the application at hand.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] A common standard class of dedicated processors is the digital signal processor (DSP).
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Since the embedded system is dedicated to specific tasks, design engineers can optimize it to reduce the size and cost of the product and increase its reliability and performance.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are mass-produced, benefiting from economies of scale.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Embedded systems range in size from portable personal devices such as digital watches and MP3 players to bigger machines like home appliances, industrial assembly lines, robots, transport vehicles, traffic light controllers, and medical imaging systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Often they constitute subsystems of other machines like avionics in aircraft and astrionics in spacecraft.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Large installations like factories, pipelines, and electrical grids rely on multiple embedded systems networked together.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Generalized through software customization, embedded systems such as programmable logic controllers frequently comprise their functional units.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The origins of the microprocessor and the microcontroller can be traced back to the MOS integrated circuit, which is an integrated circuit chip fabricated from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors) and was developed in the early 1960s.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] By 1964, MOS chips had reached higher transistor density and lower manufacturing costs than bipolar chips.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to large-scale integration (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS chip by the late 1960s.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The application of MOS LSI chips to computing was the basis for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete computer processor system could be contained on several MOS LSI chips.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released in 1971.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] One of the first recognizably modern embedded systems was the Apollo Guidance Computer, developed ca.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] 1965 by Charles Stark Draper at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] At the project's inception, the Apollo guidance computer was considered the riskiest item in the Apollo project as it employed the then newly developed monolithic integrated circuits to reduce the computer's size and weight.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] An early mass-produced embedded system was the Autonetics D-17 guidance computer for the Minuteman missile, released in 1961.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] When the Minuteman II went into production in 1966, the D-17 was replaced with a new computer that represented the first high-volume use of integrated circuits.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Since these early applications in the 1960s, embedded systems have come down in price and there has been a dramatic rise in processing power and functionality.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] An early microprocessor, the Intel 4004 (released in 1971), was designed for calculators and other small systems but still required external memory and support chips.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] By the early 1980s, memory, input and output system components had been integrated into the same chip as the processor, forming a microcontroller.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Microcontrollers find applications where a general-purpose computer would be too costly.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] As the cost of microprocessors and microcontrollers fell, the prevalence of embedded systems increased.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] A comparatively low-cost microcontroller may be programmed to fulfill the same role as a large number of separate components.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] With microcontrollers, it became feasible to replace, even in consumer products, expensive knob-based analog components such as potentiometers and variable capacitors with up/down buttons or knobs read out by a microprocessor.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Although in this context an embedded system is usually more complex than a traditional solution, most of the complexity is contained within the microcontroller itself.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Very few additional components may be needed and most of the design effort is in the software.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Software prototype and test can be quicker compared with the design and construction of a new circuit not using an embedded processor.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Embedded systems are commonly found in consumer, industrial, automotive, home appliances, medical, telecommunication, commercial, aerospace and military applications.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Telecommunications systems employ numerous embedded systems from telephone switches for the network to cell phones at the end user.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Computer networking uses dedicated routers and network bridges to route data.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Consumer electronics include MP3 players, television sets, mobile phones, video game consoles, digital cameras, GPS receivers, and printers.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Household appliances, such as microwave ovens, washing machines and dishwashers, include embedded systems to provide flexibility, efficiency and features.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Advanced heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems use networked thermostats to more accurately and efficiently control temperature that can change by time of day and season.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Home automation uses wired and wireless networking that can be used to control lights, climate, security, audio/visual, surveillance, etc., all of which use embedded devices for sensing and controlling.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Transportation systems from flight to automobiles increasingly use embedded systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] New airplanes contain advanced avionics such as inertial guidance systems and GPS receivers that also have considerable safety requirements.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Spacecraft rely on astrionics systems for trajectory correction.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Various electric motors — brushless DC motors, induction motors and DC motors — use electronic motor controllers.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Automobiles, electric vehicles, and hybrid vehicles increasingly use embedded systems to maximize efficiency and reduce pollution.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Other automotive safety systems using embedded systems include anti-lock braking system (ABS), electronic stability control (ESC/ESP), traction control (TCS) and automatic four-wheel drive.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Medical equipment uses embedded systems for monitoring, and various medical imaging (positron emission tomography (PET), single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) for non-invasive internal inspections.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Embedded systems within medical equipment are often powered by industrial computers.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Embedded systems are used for safety-critical systems in aerospace and defense industries.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Unless connected to wired or wireless networks via on-chip 3G cellular or other methods for IoT monitoring and control purposes, these systems can be isolated from hacking and thus be more secure.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] For fire safety, the systems can be designed to have a greater ability to handle higher temperatures and continue to operate.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In dealing with security, the embedded systems can be self-sufficient and be able to deal with cut electrical and communication systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Miniature wireless devices called motes are networked wireless sensors.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] These motes are completely self-contained and will typically run off a battery source for years before the batteries need to be changed or charged.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Embedded systems are designed to perform a specific task, in contrast with general-purpose computers designed for multiple tasks.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Some have real-time performance constraints that must be met, for reasons such as safety and usability; others may have low or no performance requirements, allowing the system hardware to be simplified to reduce costs.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Embedded systems are not always standalone devices.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Many embedded systems are a small part within a larger device that serves a more general purpose.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] For example, the Gibson Robot Guitar features an embedded system for tuning the strings, but the overall purpose of the Robot Guitar is to play music.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Similarly, an embedded system in an automobile provides a specific function as a subsystem of the car itself.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The program instructions written for embedded systems are referred to as firmware, and are stored in read-only memory or flash memory chips.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] They run with limited computer hardware resources: little memory, small or non-existent keyboard or screen.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Embedded systems range from no user interface at all, in systems dedicated to one task, to complex graphical user interfaces that resemble modern computer desktop operating systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Simple embedded devices use buttons, light-emitting diodes (LED), graphic or character liquid-crystal displays (LCD) with a simple menu system.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] More sophisticated devices that use a graphical screen with touch sensing or screen-edge soft keys provide flexibility while minimizing space used: the meaning of the buttons can change with the screen, and selection involves the natural behavior of pointing at what is desired.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Some systems provide user interface remotely with the help of a serial (e.g.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] This approach extends the capabilities of the embedded system, avoids the cost of a display, simplifies the board support package (BSP) and allows designers to build a rich user interface on the PC.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] A good example of this is the combination of an embedded HTTP server running on an embedded device (such as an IP camera or a network router).
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The user interface is displayed in a web browser on a PC connected to the device.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Examples of properties of typical embedded computers when compared with general-purpose counterparts are low power consumption, small size, rugged operating ranges, and low per-unit cost.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] This comes at the expense of limited processing resources.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Numerous microcontrollers have been developed for embedded systems use.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] General-purpose microprocessors are also used in embedded systems, but generally require more support circuitry than microcontrollers.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] PC/104 and PC/104+ are examples of standards for ready-made computer boards intended for small, low-volume embedded and ruggedized systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] These are mostly x86-based and often physically small compared to a standard PC, although still large compared to most simple (8/16-bit) embedded systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] They may use a standard operating system such as Linux or NetBSD or an embedded real-time operating system (RTOS) such as MicroC/OS-II, QNX or VxWorks.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In certain applications, where small size or power efficiency are not primary concerns, the components used may be compatible with those used in general-purpose x86 personal computers.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Boards such as the VIA EPIA range help to bridge the gap by being PC-compatible but highly integrated, physically smaller or have other attributes making them attractive to embedded engineers.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The advantage of this approach is that low-cost commodity components may be used along with the same software development tools used for general software development.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Systems built in this way are still regarded as embedded since they are integrated into larger devices and fulfill a single role.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Examples of devices that may adopt this approach are automated teller machines (ATM) and arcade machines, which contain code specific to the application.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] However, most ready-made embedded systems boards are not PC-centered and do not use the ISA or PCI buses.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] When a system-on-a-chip processor is involved, there may be little benefit to having a standardized bus connecting discrete components, and the environment for both hardware and software tools may be very different.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] One common design style uses a small system module, perhaps the size of a business card, holding high density BGA chips such as an ARM-based system-on-a-chip processor and peripherals, external flash memory for storage, and DRAM for runtime memory.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The module vendor will usually provide boot software and make sure there is a selection of operating systems, usually including Linux and some real-time choices.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] These modules can be manufactured in high volume, by organizations familiar with their specialized testing issues and combined with much lower volume custom mainboards with application-specific external peripherals.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Prominent examples of this approach include Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] A system on a chip (SoC) contains a complete system - consisting of multiple processors, multipliers, caches, even different types of memory and commonly various peripherals like interfaces for wired or wireless communication on a single chip.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Often graphics processing units (GPU) and DSPs are included such chips.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] SoCs can be implemented as an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) or using a field-programmable gate array (FPGA), which typically can be reconfigured.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] ASIC implementations are common for very-high-volume embedded systems like mobile phones and smartphones.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] ASIC or FPGA implementations may be used for not-so-high-volume embedded systems with special needs in terms of signal processing performance, interfaces and reliability, like in avionics.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] As with other software, embedded system designers use compilers, assemblers, and debuggers to develop embedded system software.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Embedded software often requires a variety of development tools, including programming languages such as C++, Rust, or Python, and frameworks like Qt for graphical interfaces.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] These tools enable developers to create efficient, scalable, and feature-rich applications tailored to the specific requirements of embedded systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The choice of tools is driven by factors such as real-time performance, integration with hardware, or energy efficiency.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] As the complexity of embedded systems grows, higher-level tools and operating systems are migrating into machinery where it makes sense.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] For example, cellphones, personal digital assistants and other consumer computers often need significant software that is purchased or provided by a person other than the manufacturer of the electronics.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In these systems, an open programming environment such as Linux, NetBSD, FreeBSD, OSGi or Embedded Java is required so that the third-party software provider can sell to a large market.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Embedded debugging may be performed at different levels, depending on the facilities available.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Unless restricted to external debugging, the programmer can typically load and run software through the tools, view the code running in the processor, and start or stop its operation.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The view of the code may be as high-level programming language, assembly code or a mixture of both.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Real-time operating systems often support tracing of operating system events.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] A graphical view is presented by a host PC tool, based on a recording of the system behavior.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The trace recording can be performed in software, by the RTOS, or by special tracing hardware.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] RTOS tracing allows developers to understand timing and performance issues of the software system and gives a good understanding of the high-level system behaviors.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Trace recording in embedded systems can be achieved using hardware or software solutions.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Software-based trace recording does not require specialized debugging hardware and can be used to record traces in deployed devices, but it can have an impact on CPU and RAM usage.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] One example of a software-based tracing method used in RTOS environments is the use of empty macros which are invoked by the operating system at strategic places in the code, and can be implemented to serve as hooks.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Embedded systems often reside in machines that are expected to run continuously for years without error, and in some cases, recover by themselves if an error occurs.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Therefore, the software is usually developed and tested more carefully than that for personal computers, and unreliable mechanical moving parts such as disk drives, switches or buttons are avoided.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] For high-volume systems such as mobile phones, minimizing cost is usually the primary design consideration.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Engineers typically select hardware that is just good enough to implement the necessary functions.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] For low-volume or prototype embedded systems, general-purpose computers may be adapted by limiting the programs or by replacing the operating system with an RTOS.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In 1978 National Electrical Manufacturers Association released ICS 3-1978, a standard for programmable microcontrollers, including almost any computer-based controllers, such as single-board computers, numerical, and event-based controllers.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] There are several different types of software architecture in common use.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In this design, the software simply has a loop which monitors the input devices.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The loop calls subroutines, each of which manages a part of the hardware or software.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Hence it is called a simple control loop or programmed input-output.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are predominantly controlled by interrupts.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] This means that tasks performed by the system are triggered by different kinds of events; an interrupt could be generated, for example, by a timer at a predefined interval, or by a serial port controller receiving data.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] This architecture is used if event handlers need low latency, and the event handlers are short and simple.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] These systems run a simple task in a main loop also, but this task is not very sensitive to unexpected delays.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Sometimes the interrupt handler will add longer tasks to a queue structure.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Later, after the interrupt handler has finished, these tasks are executed by the main loop.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] This method brings the system close to a multitasking kernel with discrete processes.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Cooperative multitasking is very similar to the simple control loop scheme, except that the loop is hidden in an API.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The programmer defines a series of tasks, and each task gets its own environment to run in.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] When a task is idle, it calls an idle routine, which passes control to another task.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The advantages and disadvantages are similar to those of the control loop, except that adding new software is easier, by simply writing a new task, or adding to the queue.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In this type of system, a low-level piece of code switches between tasks or threads based on a timer that invokes an interrupt.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] This is the level at which the system is generally considered to have an operating system kernel.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Depending on how much functionality is required, it introduces more or less of the complexities associated with managing multiple tasks running conceptually in parallel.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Because of these complexities, it is common for organizations to use an off-the-shelf RTOS, allowing the application programmers to concentrate on device functionality rather than operating system services.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The choice to include an RTOS brings in its own issues, however, as the selection must be made prior to starting the application development process.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] This timing forces developers to choose the embedded operating system for their device based on current requirements and so restricts future options to a large extent.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] These trends are leading to the uptake of embedded middleware in addition to an RTOS.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] A microkernel allocates memory and switches the CPU to different threads of execution.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] User-mode processes implement major functions such as file systems, network interfaces, etc.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Exokernels communicate efficiently by normal subroutine calls.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] The hardware and all the software in the system are available to and extensible by application programmers.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] A monolithic kernel is a relatively large kernel with sophisticated capabilities adapted to suit an embedded environment.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] This gives programmers an environment similar to a desktop operating system like Linux or Microsoft Windows, and is therefore very productive for development.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] On the downside, it requires considerably more hardware resources, is often more expensive, and, because of the complexity of these kernels, can be less predictable and reliable.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Common examples of embedded monolithic kernels are embedded Linux, VXWorks and Windows CE.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] Despite the increased cost in hardware, this type of embedded system is increasing in popularity, especially on the more powerful embedded devices such as wireless routers and GPS navigation systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In addition to the core operating system, many embedded systems have additional upper-layer software components.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] These components include networking protocol stacks like CAN, TCP/IP, FTP, HTTP, and HTTPS, and storage capabilities like FAT and flash memory management systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] If the embedded device has audio and video capabilities, then the appropriate drivers and codecs will be present in the system.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In the case of the monolithic kernels, many of these software layers may be included in the kernel.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In the RTOS category, the availability of additional software components depends on the commercial offering.
[src:code-generation-embedded/embedded-system] In the automotive sector, AUTOSAR is a standard architecture for embedded software.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] In computing, **firmware** (**FW**) is software that provides low-level control of computer hardware.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] For a relatively simple device, firmware may perform all control, monitoring and data manipulation functionality.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] For a more complex device, firmware may provide only relatively low-level control as well as hardware abstraction to higher-level software such as an operating system.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Firmware is found in a wide range of computing devices, including personal computers, smartphones, home appliances, vehicles, computer peripherals and in many of the integrated circuits inside each of these larger systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Firmware is stored in non-volatile memory – either read-only memory (ROM) or programmable memory such as EPROM, EEPROM, or flash.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Changing a device's firmware stored in ROM requires physically replacing the memory chip or the device itself.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Programmable firmware memory can be reprogrammed via a procedure sometimes called *flashing*.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Common reasons for changing firmware include fixing bugs and adding features.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Ascher Opler used the term *firmware* in a 1967 *Datamation* article, as an intermediary term between *hardware* and *software*.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Opler projected that fourth-generation computer systems would have a writable control store (a small specialized high-speed memory) into which microcode firmware would be loaded.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Many software functions would be moved to microcode, and instruction sets could be customized, with different firmware loaded for different instruction sets.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] As computers began to increase in complexity, it became clear that various programs needed to first be initiated and run to provide a consistent environment necessary for running more complex programs at the user's discretion.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] This required programming the computer to run those programs automatically.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Furthermore, as companies, universities, and marketers wanted to sell computers to laypeople with little technical knowledge, greater automation became necessary to allow a layperson to easily run programs for practical purposes.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] This gave rise to a kind of software that a user would not consciously run, and it led to software that a lay user would not even know about.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] As originally used, firmware contrasted with hardware (the CPU itself) and software (normal instructions executing on a CPU).
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] It was not composed of CPU machine instructions, but of lower-level microcode involved in the implementation of machine instructions.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] It existed on the boundary between hardware and software; thus the name *firmware*.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] In some respects, the various firmware components are as important as the operating system in a working computer.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] However, unlike most modern operating systems, firmware rarely has a well-evolved automatic mechanism of updating itself to fix any functionality issues detected after shipping the unit.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] A computer's firmware may be manually updated by a user via a small utility program.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] In contrast, firmware in mass storage devices (hard-disk drives, optical disc drives, flash memory storage e.g., solid state drive) is less frequently updated, even when flash memory (rather than ROM, EEPROM) storage is used for the firmware.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Most computer peripherals are themselves special-purpose computers.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Devices such as printers, scanners, webcams, and USB flash drives have internally-stored firmware; some devices may also permit field upgrading of their firmware.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] For modern, simpler devices, such as USB keyboards, USB mouses and USB sound cards, the trend is to store the firmware in on-chip memory in the device's microcontroller, as opposed to storing it in a separate EEPROM chip.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Consumer products like digital cameras and portable music players support firmware upgrades.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] In digital cameras, firmware upgrades address bugs in the operation, along with adding new functions to the camera's operation.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Some companies use firmware updates to add new playable file formats (codecs).
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Other features that may change with firmware updates include the user interface or even the battery life.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Since 1996, most automobiles have employed an on-board computer and various sensors to detect mechanical problems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] As of 2010, modern vehicles also employ computer-controlled anti-lock braking systems (ABS) and computer-operated transmission control units (TCUs).
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] The driver can also get in-dash information while driving in this manner, such as real-time fuel economy and tire pressure readings.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Local dealers can update most vehicle firmware.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Sometimes, third parties develop an unofficial new or modified ("aftermarket") version of firmware to provide new features or to unlock hidden functionality; this is referred to as custom firmware.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] An example is Rockbox as a firmware replacement for portable media players.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] There are many homebrew projects for various devices, which often unlock general-purpose computing functionality in previously limited devices (e.g., running Doom on iPods).
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Firmware hacks usually take advantage of the firmware update facility on many devices to install or run themselves.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Some, however, must resort to exploits to run, because the manufacturer has attempted to lock the hardware to stop it from running unlicensed code.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Although the Kaspersky Lab report did not explicitly claim that this group is part of the United States National Security Agency (NSA), evidence obtained from the code of various Equation Group software suggests that they are part of the NSA.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Researchers from the Kaspersky Lab categorized the undertakings by Equation Group as the most advanced hacking operation ever uncovered, also documenting around 500 infections caused by the Equation Group in at least 42 countries.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Mark Shuttleworth, the founder of the company Canonical, which created the Ubuntu Linux distribution, has described proprietary firmware as a security risk, saying that "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend" and calling firmware "a trojan horse of monumental proportions".
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] As a potential solution to this problem, he has called for declarative firmware, which would describe "hardware linkage and dependencies" and "should not include executable code".
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Firmware should be open-source so that the code can be checked and verified.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Custom firmware hacks have also focused on injecting malware into devices such as smartphones or USB devices.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] One such smartphone injection was demonstrated on the Symbian OS at MalCon, a hacker convention.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] A USB device firmware hack called BadUSB was presented at the Black Hat USA 2014 conference, demonstrating how a USB flash drive microcontroller can be reprogrammed to spoof various other device types to take control of a computer, exfiltrate data, or spy on the user.
[src:code-generation-embedded/firmware] Other security researchers have worked further on how to exploit the principles behind BadUSB, releasing at the same time the source code of hacking tools that can be used to modify the behavior of different USB devices.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Model-based design provides an efficient approach for establishing a common framework for communication throughout the design process while supporting the development cycle (V-model).
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] 4. integrating all these phases by deploying the controller.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] The model-based design is significantly different from traditional design methodology.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Rather than using complex structures and extensive software code, designers can use Model-based design to define plant models with advanced functional characteristics using continuous-time and discrete-time building blocks.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] These built models used with simulation tools can lead to rapid prototyping, software testing, and verification.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Not only is the testing and verification process enhanced, but also, in some cases, hardware-in-the-loop simulation can be used with the new design paradigm to perform testing of dynamic effects on the system more quickly and much more efficiently than with traditional design methodology.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] As early as the 1920s two aspects of engineering, control theory and control systems, converged to make large-scale integrated systems possible.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] In those early days controls systems were commonly used in the industrial environment.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Large process facilities started using process controllers for regulating continuous variables such as temperature, pressure, and flow rate.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Electrical relays built into ladder-like networks were one of the first discrete control devices to automate an entire manufacturing process.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Control systems gained momentum, primarily in the automotive and aerospace sectors.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] In the 1950s and 1960s, the push to space generated interest in embedded control systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Engineers constructed control systems such as engine control units and flight simulators, that could be part of the end product.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] By the end of the twentieth century, embedded control systems were ubiquitous, as even major household consumer appliances such as washing machines and air conditioners contained complex and advanced control algorithms, making them much more "intelligent".
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] In 1969, the first computer-based controllers were introduced.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] These early programmable logic controllers (PLC) mimicked the operations of already available discrete control technologies that used the out-dated relay ladders.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] The advent of PC technology brought a drastic shift in the process and discrete control market.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] An off-the-shelf desktop loaded with adequate hardware and software can run an entire process unit, and execute complex and established PID algorithms or work as a Distributed Control System (DCS).
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] The mathematical model conceived in step 1 is used to identify dynamic characteristics of the plant model.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] A controller can then be synthesized based on these characteristics.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Offline simulation and real-time simulation.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] The time response of the dynamic system to complex, time-varying inputs is investigated.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] This is done by simulating a simple LTI (Linear Time-Invariant) model, or by simulating a non-linear model of the plant with the controller.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Simulation allows specification, requirements, and modeling errors to be found immediately, rather than later in the design effort.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Real-time simulation can be done by automatically generating code for the controller developed in step 2.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] This code can be deployed to a special real-time prototyping computer that can run the code and control the operation of the plant.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] If a plant prototype is not available, or testing on the prototype is dangerous or expensive, code can be automatically generated from the plant model.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] This code can be deployed to the special real-time computer that can be connected to the target processor with running controller code.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Thus a controller can be tested in real-time against a real-time plant model.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Ideally this is done via code generation from the controller developed in step 2.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] It is unlikely that the controller will work on the actual system as well as it did in simulation, so an iterative debugging process is carried out by analyzing results on the actual target and updating the controller model.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Model-based design tools allow all these iterative steps to be performed in a unified visual environment.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] The disadvantages of model-based design are fairly well understood this late in development lifecycle of the product and development.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] While Model-based design has the ability to simulate test scenarios and interpret simulations well, in real world production environments, it is often not suitable.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Over reliance on a given toolchain can lead to significant rework and possibly compromise entire engineering approaches.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] While it's suitable for bench work, the choice to use this for a production system should be made very carefully.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Because of the limitations of graphical tools, design engineers previously relied heavily on text-based programming and mathematical models.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] However, developing these models was time-consuming, and highly prone to error.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] In addition, debugging text-based programs is a tedious process, requiring much trial and error before a final fault-free model could be created, especially since mathematical models undergo unseen changes during the translation through the various design stages.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Graphical modeling tools aim to improve these aspects of design.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] These tools provide a very generic and unified graphical modeling environment, and they reduce the complexity of model designs by breaking them into hierarchies of individual design blocks.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Designers can thus achieve multiple levels of model fidelity by simply substituting one block element with another.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Graphical models also help engineers to conceptualize the entire system and simplify the process of transporting the model from one stage to another in the design process.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] Boeing's simulator EASY5 was among the first modeling tools to be provided with a graphical user interface, together with AMESim, a multi-domain, multi-level platform based on the Bond Graph theory.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] This was soon followed by tool like 20-sim and Dymola, which allowed models to be composed of physical components like masses, springs, resistors, etc.
[src:code-generation-embedded/model-based-design] These were later followed by many other modern tools such as Simulink and LabVIEW.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] The term is usually applied to analysis performed by an automated tool, with human analysis typically being called "program understanding", program comprehension, or code review.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] In the last of these, software inspection and software walkthroughs are also used.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] In most cases the analysis is performed on some version of a program's source code, and, in other cases, on some form of its object code.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] The discipline of static analysis should not be confused with linting, which is the process of checking for coding style mistakes.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] The sophistication of the analysis performed by tools varies from those that only consider the behaviour of individual statements and declarations, to those that include the complete source code of a program in their analysis.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] The uses of the information obtained from the analysis vary from highlighting possible coding errors (e.g., the lint tool) to formal methods that mathematically prove properties about a given program (e.g., its behaviour matches that of its specification).
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] Software metrics and reverse engineering can be described as forms of static analysis.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] Deriving software metrics and static analysis are increasingly deployed together, especially in creation of embedded systems, by defining so-called *software quality objectives*.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] A growing commercial use of static analysis is in the verification of properties of software used in safety-critical computer systems and locating potentially vulnerable code.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] Nuclear software: In the UK the Office for Nuclear Regulation (ONR) recommends the use of static analysis on reactor protection systems.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] Aviation software (in combination with dynamic analysis).
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] Automotive & Machines (functional safety features form an integral part of each automotive product development phase, ISO 26262, section 8).
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] A study in 2012 by VDC Research reported that 28.7% of the embedded software engineers surveyed use static analysis tools and 39.7% expect to use them within 2 years.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] A study from 2010 found that 60% of the interviewed developers in European research projects made at least use of their basic IDE built-in static analyzers.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] However, only about 10% employed an additional other (and perhaps more advanced) analysis tool.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] In the application security industry the name static application security testing (SAST) is also used.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] SAST is an important part of Security Development Lifecycles (SDLs) such as the SDL defined by Microsoft and a common practice in software companies.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] The OMG (Object Management Group) published a study regarding the types of software analysis required for software quality measurement and assessment.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] This document on "How to Deliver Resilient, Secure, Efficient, and Easily Changed IT Systems in Line with CISQ Recommendations" describes three levels of software analysis.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes place within a specific program or subroutine, without connecting to the context of that program.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes into account the interactions between unit programs, but without being limited to one specific technology or programming language.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] A further level of software analysis can be defined.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes into account the business/mission layer terms, rules and processes that are implemented within the software system for its operation as part of enterprise or program/mission layer activities.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] These elements are implemented without being limited to one specific technology or programming language and in many cases are distributed across multiple languages, but are statically extracted and analyzed for system understanding for mission assurance.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] Many static analysis tools use intermediate representations of programs to examine the structure of source code without executing the program.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] For this purpose, abstract syntax trees (ASTs) are commonly used, since they provide a structured representation of a program's syntactic elements.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] Formal methods is the term applied to the analysis of software (and computer hardware) whose results are obtained purely through the use of rigorous mathematical methods.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] The mathematical techniques used include denotational semantics, axiomatic semantics, operational semantics, and abstract interpretation.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] This result dates from the works of Church, Gödel and Turing in the 1930s (see: Halting problem and Rice's theorem).
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] As with many undecidable questions, one can still attempt to give useful approximate solutions.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] Data-driven static analysis leverages extensive codebases to infer coding rules and improve the accuracy of the analysis.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] For instance, one can use all Java open-source packages available on GitHub to learn good analysis strategies.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] The rule inference can use machine learning techniques.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] It is also possible to learn from a large amount of past fixes and warnings.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] For certain types of warnings, it is possible to design and implement automated remediation techniques.
[src:code-generation-embedded/static-program-analysis] For example, Logozzo and Ball have proposed automated remediations for C# *cccheck*.
